<h1>ONAM</h1>
</div>
<div style="text-align:center">
<img src="https://www.deccanchronicle.com/h-upload/2024/09/15/1841987-onam.webp" alt="">
</div>

<div>
<p>
Onam is the most important festival of Kerala, celebrated with great joy and excitement by people of all communities. It usually falls in the month of August or September and lasts for ten days. Onam is also known as the harvest festival of Kerala.

According to legend, Onam is celebrated to welcome King Mahabali, the kind and generous ruler who once ruled Kerala. People believe that King Mahabali visits his people every year during Onam to see them happy and prosperous.

The festival is marked by many cultural traditions. People decorate their homes with beautiful flower carpets called Pookkalam. Delicious traditional feasts known as Onam Sadhya are prepared and served on banana leaves. Various art forms and games like Vallam Kali (boat race), Pulikali (tiger dance), and folk music add more charm to the celebrations. People also wear new clothes and enjoy spending time with family and friends.

Onam is not just about fun and feasting, it also teaches values of unity, equality, and cultural pride. It brings people together, regardless of religion or caste, to celebrate Keralaâ€™s rich traditions and heritage.

In conclusion, Onam is a festival of happiness, prosperity, and togetherness. It reflects the cultural beauty of Kerala and spreads the message of love, harmony, and peace.
 </p>
